{
  "family": "Hofmann-Löffler-Freytag Reaction (Remote Functionalization)",
  "candidate": {
    "substrate_smiles": [
      "CCCCN(C)Cl"
    ],
    "product_smiles": [
      "C1CCCN1C"
    ],
    "optional_reagent_smiles": [
      "O",
      "[H+]"
    ],
    "rationale": "This is a classic and simple example of the Hofmann-Löffler-Freytag reaction. N-chloro-N-methylbutan-1-amine, upon treatment with acid and light (or heat), undergoes a 1,5-hydrogen atom transfer via a nitrogen-centered radical. The resulting carbon-centered radical then abstracts the chlorine atom from the protonated amine, forming a delta-chloroamine intermediate. Subsequent intramolecular nucleophilic substitution (cyclization) upon neutralization yields the final product, N-methylpyrrolidine. This example clearly demonstrates the key remote C-H functionalization and pyrrolidine ring formation characteristic of the reaction.",
    "collision_avoidance_note": "The substrate is a simple acyclic N-haloamine, and the product is a simple pyrrolidine. This avoids complex ring systems, arenes, or other functional groups that could cause collisions with unrelated named reactions. The core transformation is the formation of a C-N bond at a delta-position relative to the initial nitrogen, which is highly specific to this reaction family."
  }
}
